<Layout title="Swimming Metrics for Surfers — What Helps and What Doesn’t - Surf Deeper" description="A pragmatic look at swimming metrics (SWOLF, stroke rate, stroke length, pace) and which ones actually matter for surfers.">
  <header class="page-header">
    <h1>Swimming Metrics for Surfers</h1>
    <p class="page-subtitle">What helps, what doesn’t, and why</p>
  </header>

  <article class="technique-article">
    <section>
      <h2>Useful Metrics</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>RPE (Rate of Perceived Exertion) and breath cadence</li>
        <li>Repeatable pace over short repeats at easy effort</li>
        <li>Heart rate trends (lower for same pace over time)</li>
        <li>Consistency: even pacing and relaxed form</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Contextual Metrics</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Stroke Rate (cadence): spikes for sprints, moderate for cruising</li>
        <li>Stroke Length: helps economy but not at the cost of a slipping catch</li>
        <li>EVF quality as a qualitative metric: clean catches per length</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Misleading or Overrated</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>SWOLF: pool-specific and boardless; surfing adds buoyancy and different goals</li>
        <li>Absolute pace: wetsuits, chop, and currents skew comparisons</li>
        <li>Counting strokes alone: ignores catch quality and body position</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What to Track in Practice</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Easy aerobic swims with nasal breathing and calm exhale</li>
        <li>Short technique sets prioritizing EVF and relaxed shoulders</li>
        <li>Occasional cadence-focused sprints while maintaining a clean catch</li>
        <li>Subjective calm under stress and post-set recovery time</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Related Reading</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/guides/stroke-rate-vs-stroke-length">Stroke Rate vs Stroke Length</a></li>
        <li><a href="/guides/swimming-for-surfers">Swimming for Surfers</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>

